d distinguished career. He founded the Institute of Islamic Studies at McGill University and served as director of the Center for the Study of World Religions at Harvard University. Smith emphasized the place of the scholarly study of Islam in the Western academy long before Islam occupied its current position at the center of global politics, challenged the notion of monolithic world religions, and argued for the importance of dialogical processes and a personalist approach to the study of religion. Contributors to this volume, many of whom were Smith's students, provide a wide-ranging exploration of his influence and legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCollege teachersvBiography. 0aIslam. 0aReligionsxStudy and teaching. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aAitken, Ellen Bradshaw, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAitken, Ellen Bradshaw, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBilimoria, Purushottama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarman, John B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoburn, Thomas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Harvey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEck, Diana L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawley, John Stratton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Jonathan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb